</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeenmalikyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen MaliKyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/2/02 8:37:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=327.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Latest Recipe for War...</span><hr size=1> Hiya Rheaton,<br>
<br>
I have to disagree with you. Firstly, the analogy you use of punishing a child who has done wrong is not fitting. Iraq is not a "wayward child" in need of US "parenting".<br>
<br>
Secondly, UN resolutions only have the teeth the Security council puts into them. What does that mean? It means that if the security council in 1991 had voted to enforce its resolutions with force the world would be kicking Saddam in the a<i></i>ss today. The fact is that the Security Council voted to use sanctions, rather than force.<br>
<br>
Thirdly, Saddam is where he is (weapons and all) due to the blunder of former President Bush. Our military might in the Persian Gulf would have completely dislodged Saddam from power if President Bush (the commander in chief) had the will to use that power to complete the job. Former President Bush lacked the fortitude to commit our troops to urban warfare in Bagdahd.<br>
<br>
Finally, it is the faults of the UN Security Council and the Former Bush administration that puts us where we are at today with Iraq. We can't reasonably see it any other way.<br>
<br>
The solution is <i><b>not</i></b> to wage a new unprovoked war against Iraq. It is put faith in the process of peace that the UN Security council implemented and hope it works. If Saddam does allow inspectors and they find nothing I think the world will be completely relieved and we can all move on to what really matters and that is securing our borders against terror. <p><HTML><IMG SRC="http://64.81.30.48/lurisig.jpg" HSPACE="150" WIDTH="330" HEIGHT="185" BORDER="0"> </HTML></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucnjmorris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>cnjmorris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 227<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/2/02 9:01:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=327.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Latest Recipe for War...</span><hr size=1> Its lose lose.  I am glad I don't have to be the one to decide which it the bigger loss.<br>
<br>
Saddam is insane.  He claimed they could beat the US back int he Guilf days and I think he actually believed it.  It was at that point I knew he wasn't working with a full deck.<br>
<br>
So now we are faced with the decision to let him stockpile more and more weapons or try to stop him.  So we attack and he uses chemicals and hides behinds civilians.  Or we don't attack and next time they fly a plane into the sears tower, only this time there was a canister of air born virus in a suitcase that just loved the explosions spreading power.<br>
<br>
You know what... this isn't about Bush, this isn't about Clinton or Bush Sr.  There is no Republican or Democratic... or, there is and shouldn't be.<br>
<br>
This is a time of tought decisions.  Do you have a solution?  Think hard before you say yes.  Think really hard.  You have a solution that will save lives not only now but in the FUTURE.  You have a solution that will protect us not only from Saddam but from the terrorists he is KNOWN to support?<br>
<br>
I don't have the answer.  Should we attack?  I don't know, but I don't know that we shouldn't either.  <br>
<br>
People saying that this is all about Oil... where have you been, what planet has your mind been vacationing on?  Maybe oil is an issue, but to act like its the only motivation... do you think that Bush didn't know anyone who has died to terrorists?  I give him a little more credit than saying this is all about oil prices.  I don't know anyone who died to terorists, I haven't even heard about a friend or an acquaintence dying to one... and yet I feel the powerful need to do SOMETHING.<br>
<br>
Should the US sit and do nothing because it doesn't know what to do?  It may be that war is a mistake, but the bigger crime would be to sit by and watch our children, our fathers, and our heroes be systematically slaughtered by un-named sources, hiding behind pawns who have been promised untold treasures in the afterlife.<br>
<br>
I am not close minded.  I am NOT saying war is the answer.  What I AM saying is that people who do nothing and sit back and criticise, ESPECIALLY those who do it on a political basis, are NOT a part of the solution.<br>
<br>
Why do I get the impression that most of these people would be supportive if some Democrat was sitting in the Whits House under the same exact situation.  All of a sudden war would be an acceptable need, and it would have nothing to do with oil... <p><img src=http://www.mindspring.com/~cnjmorris/catcen.jpg>

